post_cb({"18312205": {"ParentId": "18312186", "LastEditDate": "2013-08-19T11:33:19.217", "CommentCount": "4", "CreationDate": "2013-08-19T11:02:28.107", "OwnerUserId": "947836", "LastEditorUserId": "947836", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "18312205", "Score": "20", "Body": "<p>Function pointers don't need it, <strong>member</strong> function pointers do.</p>\n<p><code>Device::asyncUpdate</code> is member function, as you could guess because it is being bound to <code>this</code>.</p>\n<p>Here's a normative quote from n3337, 5.3.1/4</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_18312186_18312205_0\">A pointer to member is only formed when an explicit &amp; is used and its operand is a quali\ufb01ed-id not enclosed in parentheses.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-08-19T11:33:19.217"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_18312186_18312205_0": {"section_id": 6067, "quality": 0.9, "length": 9}}, "n3337": {"so_18312186_18312205_0": {"section_id": 5835, "quality": 0.9, "length": 9}}, "n4659": {"so_18312186_18312205_0": {"section_id": 7563, "quality": 0.9, "length": 9}}}, "18312186": {"CommentCount": "2", "CreationDate": "2013-08-19T11:01:27.750", "PostTypeId": "1", "AcceptedAnswerId": "18312205", "LastEditorUserId": "-1", "LastActivityDate": "2013-12-10T14:46:50.117", "LastEditDate": "2017-05-23T12:02:37.033", "ViewCount": "1039", "FavoriteCount": "5", "Title": "If ampersands aren't needed for function pointers, why does boost::bind require one?", "Id": "18312186", "Score": "9", "Body": "<p>I've always believed that function pointers don't require an ampersand:</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/16917043/do-function-pointers-need-an-ampersand\">Do function pointers need an ampersand</a></p>\n<p>Yet, every example I've seen of using <code>boost::bind</code> shows one, and my compiler - in most situations - gives a typically inscrutable error message if it's omitted.</p>\n<pre><code>synchronize(boost::bind(&amp;Device::asyncUpdate , this, \"ErrorMessage\"));  // Works\n\nsynchronize(boost::bind(Device::asyncUpdate , this, \"ErrorMessage\"));   // Fails\n</code></pre>\n<p>Am I wrong in assuming that <code>boost::bind</code>'s first parameter is basically function pointer?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><function-pointers><boost-bind>", "OwnerUserId": "1737", "AnswerCount": "1"}});